{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608453"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:31:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:31:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15998"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15998"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.09,0.19,0.59,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8689"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63460"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8689"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15998"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48913"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8606"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20796"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63460"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryological development, the mesoderm layer splits into distinct regions that give rise to different body structures. One of these regions develops in close association with the surface ectoderm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the derivatives of somatic mesoderm?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Forms the lining of body cavities","Develops into blood vessels and heart muscle","Forms smooth muscle of internal organs","Forms skeletal muscle, dermis and bones","Develops into kidneys and gonads"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esomatic mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E develops adjacent to the surface ectoderm and gives rise to the connective tissues of the body wall, including skeletal muscles, bones, and dermis of the skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other mesodermal derivatives:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmooth muscle of internal organs\u003C/strong\u003E derives from splanchnic mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood vessels and heart muscle\u003C/strong\u003E develop from cardiogenic mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKidneys and gonads\u003C/strong\u003E develop from intermediate mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELining of body cavities\u003C/strong\u003E develops from lateral plate mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the derivatives of different mesodermal regions is crucial for comprehending embryological development and the organisation of body structures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Somatic mesoderm forms the body wall, including skeletal muscle, dermis, and bones.","Somatic mesoderm develops adjacent to surface ectoderm during embryological development.","Somatic mesoderm is distinct from splanchnic mesoderm which forms visceral structures."],"references":["Philonenko ES, Shutova MV, Khomyakova EA, Vassina EM, Lebedeva OS, Kiselev SL, Lagarkova MA. Differentiation of Human Pluripotent Stem Cells into Mesodermal and Ectodermal Derivatives Is Independent of the Type of Isogenic Reprogrammed Somatic Cells. Acta Naturae. 2017 Jan-Mar;9(1):68-74. PMID: 28461976; PMCID: PMC5406662.","Gaillard R, Steegers EA, de Jongste JC, Hofman A, Jaddoe VW. Tracking of fetal growth characteristics during different trimesters and the risks of adverse birth outcomes. Int J Epidemiol. 2014 Aug;43(4):1140-53. doi: 10.1093/ije/dyu036. Epub 2014 Mar 5. PMID: 24603318; PMCID: PMC4258770","Chen X, Liu H, Li Y, Zhang W, Zhou A, Xia W, Xu S. First-trimester fetal size, accelerated growth in utero, and child neurodevelopment in a cohort study. BMC Med. 2024 Apr 29;22(1):181. doi: 10.1186/s12916-024-03390-3. PMID: 38685041; PMCID: PMC11059611","Godfrey KM, Inskip HM, Hanson MA. The long-term effects of prenatal development on growth and metabolism. Semin Reprod Med. 2011 May;29(3):257-65. doi: 10.1055/s-0031-1275518. Epub 2011 Jul 18. PMID: 21769765; PMCID: PMC3685133","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48913"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15998"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48913"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T23:03:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T23:05:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8689"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63460"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":